ria, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1248–about 1272":"about 1248–about 1272","1248–1272":"1248–1272","1250–1293":"1250–1293","1208–1271":"1208–1271","1267–1295":"1267–1295","–Male":"Deceased","about 1272":"about 1272","1259":"1259","1248":"1248","1267":"1267","about 1248":"about 1248","1295":"1295","about 1267":"about 1267","1250":"1250","1272":"1272","1271":"1271","1293":"1293","1208":"1208","Burgh by Sands, Cumberland, England":"Burgh by Sands, Cumberland, England","Gilsland, Northumberland, England":"Gilsland, Northumberland, England","Carliste  Cumbria England":"Cumbria, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Levington","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  English: locative name, variant of   Levington  , but this is an E Anglian surname and the name in S and SW England must either reflect migration or have a different origin; see (2).","2  English: locative name,  <i>Lewington</i> and  <i>Levington</i> are perhaps variant pronunciations of the Wilts surname   Lavington  . The vowel change is not recorded in the place-name, but there is some evidence for occasional raising of late Middle English [a] to early Modern English [e]. The development of intervocalic [v] to [w] is not uncommon in Middle English dialects, and original  <i>-ton</i> is often replaced in surnames with  <i>-don</i> and  <i>-den</i>. Compare therefore Johannes and Michaelis Lavynton’, 1381 in   Poll Tax   (Reading, Berks) with Mathew Lewington, 1641 in   IGI   (Reading, Berks), and Johanne Lavynton’, 1381 in   Poll Tax   (Hidden, Berks) with Josias Lewendon, 1611 in   IGI   (Hungerford, Berks); Hidden is in Hungerford parish. Compare also Mary Lewington, 1640, John Laventon, 1705 in   IGI   (Cheriton, Hants). However, these may be different surnames."],"variants":[{"name":"Poll Tax","meanings":["1  Irish, Scottish Gaelic: relationship name: apparently a reduced form of an unrecorded Gaelic name,  <b>Mac Ruanaidh</b> ‘son of  <i>Ruanadh</i>’, a personal name from Gaelic  <i>ruanaidh</i> ‘strong man, champion’. The initial  <i>C</i> comes from the final consonant of  <i>mac</i>.  Compare  Rooney  .","2  English: of uncertain origin. It might be a variant of   Crowner   ‘coroner’, once a Sussex name, with the final syllable pronounced  <i>-ey</i>. Compare Simon Croner, 1296 in   Subsidy Rolls   (Horton, Tottington, and Edburton, Sussex); Willelmus Croner, 1379 in   Poll Tax   (South Mundham, Sussex). Alternatively it might be a variant of  <i>Corney</i> with the medial  <i>-r-</i> metathesized."]},{"name":"Lewinton","meanings":["English:  see  Lewington  ."]},{"name":"IGI","meanings":["English: perhaps an altered form of   Pritchett   or   Pritchard  . Compare Katherine Pratchett, 1654, Janam Pritchett, 1675 in   IGI   (Acton by Nantwich, Cheshire); Gulielmus Pritchard, 1675, Mary Pratchett, 1698 in   IGI   (Hatfield, Herts)."]},{"name":"Lewendon","meanings":["English: variant of   Lewington  ."]},{"name":"Lavington","meanings":["English: locative name from Market and West Lavington (Wilts)."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":11,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Helewisa Levington was born about 1248, in Burgh by Sands, Cumberland, England as the daughter of Ralph Livington. She had at least 1 son with Sir Thomas Multon II of Gilsland. She died about 1272, in her hometown, at the age of 26."},"et":{"about 1248–about 1272":"umbes 1248–umbes 1272","1248–1272":"1248–1272","1250–1293":"1250–1293","1208–1271":"1208–1271","1267–1295":"1267–1295","–Male":"Surnud","about 1272":"umbes 1272","1259":"1259"